titleStmt.title: Concerto for basset clarinet and orchestra in A major, KV 622

normalization.p: First, a score of the Concerto was written in scorewriter program Sibelius. After exporting a musicXML file, two XSL stylesheets were applied. The final MEI file contained about 20% of errors and was corrected manually. Some issues like e. g. such ambiguities in placement of <slur> with both @tstamp AND @startid/ @endid were not resolved due to time-consuming activity and as they don't affect rendering.

There were several conflicts in syntax of MEI guidelines version 3.0, RNG-schema and Verovio. Some features were not able to render (e. g. division into movements, ossia in the bar 204). Those issues were commented out.

In the reference score violoncellos and contrabasses were split into separate staffs from measure 227 to measure 240. In this encoding they stay on the same staff, but placed onto separate layers with additional labels. The reason was the technical problem of rendering the additonal staff only in one segment of the score. However, this solution doesn't seem to affect its readability. In the future it should be checked if Giegling had any important reason for this layout.

projectDesc.p: The aim of the current encoding was an exact reproduction of the sore of traditional version for clarinet in A by Franz Giegling. This edition is based on 14 sources including (piecewise) autographs, prints, copies, arrangements and one review. In the Critical Report the editor provides an index of alternative readings ('Leseartenverzeichnis') with the reference to these sources. An implementing of this index could be an issue for further enhancement of the encoding as well as merging of the versions for basset clarinet and clarinet in A.

Additional cadenzas by Meyer/Wehle in bars 127 and 315 are provided for technical demonstration of choice possibilities only. However, this section could be extended with other suggestions from these clarinetists as well as with cadenzas from earlier authors such as Stanislav Krticka, Jacque Ibert, Karlheinz Stockhausen, etc.

samplingDecl.p: The encoding includes the first movement.
